Malaysia Stocks: AirAsia, Glomac, Malaysia Steel, RHB Capital

-- B y   C h a n   T i e n   H i n
-- 
2011-06-24T09:12:21Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-24/malaysia-stocks-airasia-malaysia-steel-works-rhb-capital.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Malaysia trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 5 p.m. close in  Kuala
Lumpur .  The  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI (FBMKLCI)  Index rose 1.47 points, or 0.1
percent, to 1,564.66. The gauge gained 0.1 percent this week,
its second weekly increase.        AirAsia Bhd. (AIRA)   rose 4.1 percent to 3.29 ringgit, a
record close. Airbus SAS won 200 orders for its A320neo single-
aisle model from the discount carrier in an $18 billion deal.        Glomac Bhd. (GLMC)  , a property developer, added 3.9
percent, the most since April 1, to 1.87 ringgit after fourth-
quarter profit rose 20 percent from a year earlier to 15 million
ringgit ($4.9 million). Glomac also announced a share split to
lure more investors, it said in a separate statement.        Malaysia  Steel Works (KL) Bhd. (MSW MK), a steelmaker,
gained 3.3 percent to 1.24 ringgit, the highest level since May
31, after saying it plans to invest 100 million ringgit in a new
rolling mill to tap rising demand for steel products. Malaysia
Steel is pursuing steel supply contracts valued at 1 billion
ringgit, it said in a statement.        Malaysian Airline System Bhd. (MAS)  , the national
carrier, jumped 5.5 percent to 1.53 ringgit, the steepest gain
since Dec. 22. Crude oil for August delivery fell 4.6 percent in
New York yesterday.        RHB Capital Bhd. (RHBC)   slid 3.1 percent to 8.75
ringgit, its lowest close since May 10.  CIMB Group Holdings Bhd. (CIMB) 
 and  Malayan Banking Bhd. (MAY)  , Malaysia’s two
biggest banks, scrapped rival talks to acquire RHB Capital,
ending ambitions to create Southeast Asia’s biggest lender,
according to separate company statements. CIMB gained 2 percent
to 8.68 ringgit and Malayan Banking added 0.7 percent to 8.88
ringgit.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Chan Tien Hin in Kuala Lumpur at 
